[The Kimberley is one of the 9 regions of Western Australia. It is in the northern part of Western Australia.

Mumps is a contagious disease that is caused by mumps virus. Mumps typically starts with a few days of fever, headache, muscle aches, tiredness, and loss of appetite, and is followed by swelling of salivary glands. Anyone who is not immune from either previous mumps infection or from vaccination can get mumps. Before the routine vaccination was introduced, mumps was a common illness in infants, children and young adults.

Mumps is no longer very common, but outbreaks continue to occur, most commonly where people have had prolonged, close contact with a person who has mumps, such as attending the same class, playing on the same contact sports team, or living in the same accommodation with someone who has mumps. - Mod.CP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3323826,186.]
